### Enable Next.js Experimental Instrumentation Hook

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/documentation/nextjs/faqs/cloud-providers.md

This configuration snippet enables the experimental instrumentation hook in your `next.config.js` file, which is necessary for integrating OpenTelemetry.

```javascript
{
    experimental: {
        instrumentationHook: true
    }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Register OpenTelemetry Instrumentation in Next.js

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/documentation/nextjs/faqs/cloud-providers.md

This TypeScript code registers the OpenTelemetry instrumentation for Node.js environments within your Next.js application. It ensures that the `new-relic-instrumentation.js` file is required only when the runtime is 'nodejs'.

```typescript
export async function register() {
  if (process.env.NEXT_RUNTIME === 'nodejs') {
    require('./new-relic-instrumentation.js')
  }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Externalize 3rd Party Libraries in Next.js Webpack

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/documentation/nextjs/faqs/instrument-third-party-libraries.md

This configuration for `next.config.js` externalizes supported 3rd party libraries from webpack bundling. This is necessary for the New Relic Node.js agent to effectively auto-instrument these libraries within a Next.js application, ensuring that modules are not mangled by webpack's code splitting.

```javascript
const nrExternals = require('newrelic/load-externals')

module.exports = {
  // In order for newrelic to effectively instrument a Next.js application,
  // the modules that newrelic supports should not be mangled by webpack. Thus,
  // we need to "externalize" all of the modules that newrelic supports.
  webpack: (config) => {
    nrExternals(config)
    return config
  }
}
```

